bug.short_desc: Mylyn should examine how long a query takes

long_desc.thetext:
Mylyn polls Bugzilla repositories at regular intervals. It is possible for users to set up a Mylyn repository with search criteria that will execute on our database servers for 60 seconds, 90 seconds and often up to our 180 second limit.
I've observed queries where a partial email address is searched across 6-8 plaintext fields in Bugzilla. These queries are fairly complex, time-out repeatedly after 180 seconds of execution time and, in the end, offer no benefit to the user.
It would be great if Mylyn could track the average response time of such polls -- or, at the very least, examine the response, since the terminated queries must not contain a useful payload. If the server consistently terminates queries, or takes > X seconds to respond, then perhaps the polling frequency should be reduced, and the user should be encouraged to reduce the complexity of their query.

I understand that in order to prevent such queries becoming part of the average script kiddies arsenal, you're reluctant to provide examples of such queries.
I also understand the problem, (remember bug 196056?), and see several approaches to it.
1) Someone can try "harden" bugzilla, where certain queries in combination with certain user agents and/or user ID's are refused by some sort of "device rule", like blocking ios 6.1 from exchange servers. Needs a knowledge base on the server side, or an automatic 404 on queries that took too long last time, i.e. "auto-blacklist".
2) Someone can make Mylyn "preflight" queries, so that we sort of warn on whether the query is specific enough, UI similar to a "password strength bar", to stimulate people to be specific. This would require building a knowledge base.
3) Someone can make Mylyn queries "adaptive" by refusing to repeat queries that took too long last time, with suitable feedback in the Tasklist. This would require the possibility to turn individual queries on or off programmatically.
4) Simplest and presumably least effective, only adding a warning to the Query in the Tasklist if the query exceeds a certain time.
Let's discuss further. Interesting problem Denis!

Created attachment 227684 Screenshot
> Let's discuss further. Interesting problem Denis!
Indeed! Every time I open a bug against Mylyn it's because the project's popularity is causing me some grief. That is a good thing.
> you're reluctant to provide examples of such queries.
I only see the slow SQL queries, but if I interpret them, I see that it's an email string that is searched across many fields in all our comments.
Of course, our users can do this with the web UI, but the client ends up timing out, which is feedback. The use-case we have now has Mylyn consuming those same resources day after day without ever providing a clue to the user that the queries are wasteful.
The screenshot above shows you an example of the type of query I'm seeing. Enter your email address and ask Bugzilla to search for you in every field. The query will run for about 3 minutes until the server returns an Internal Server Error.
During those three minutes, one Apache handler is being used, and one database thread is consuming resources of one CPU core or more.
> 1) Someone can try "harden" bugzilla,
Bugzilla is easily abused, but so far we seem to be capable of handling the abuse. The 3-minute query limit is part of our home-brewed MySQL monitoring solution. Otherwise, the query would run to completion, whether or not the Apache client times out or not.

Here is what I have found in the mylyn sources.
1) When I create this kind of query using the form we get SocketTimeOutExeption but create the query.
Maybe we can here delete the new query to avoid an long running query.
2) When I create this kind of query using the form after I change the SOCKET_TIMEOUT to 6 * 60 * 1000 I get an internal error but create the query.
In the Tooltip of the query in the tasklist we have the following information: Synchronized: <never> Http error: Internal Server Error
When the status is not null we add the OVERLAY_SYNC_WARNING icon to the query icon. But there is no difference which kind of status we have.
Thoughts?

Is there a performance difference between "contains" and "is" for the name field? If so we should have default selection at "is", and maybe even move the other options to the advanced tab. I also think there is a difference in bugzilla optimization between queries for Owner, Reporter, CC, Commenter, and QA, should we check MySQL indexes on name field for each?

Even though Denis raises this problem against the bugzilla connector, ill-defined long-running queries can impact all connectors. A solution should be made generic and I think raising warning in org.eclipse.mylyn.internal.tasks.core.sync.SynchronizeQueriesJob.synchronizeQuery(RepositoryQuery, SynchronizationSession, IProgressMonitor) when queries run too long is the proper way forward. It is the location of the constant MAX_HITS_REACHED, so that is also where we should have the constant MAX_QUERY_DURATION.

In the first pass we could do the following:
set the overlay and Tooltip icon to error when we have
Statuscode == RepositoryStatus.ERROR_IO and the Exception is SocketTimeoutException for Queries with LastSynchronizedTimeStamp = "<never>"
when we change the socket timeout from 3 minutes to 4 minutes we get RepositoryStatus.ERROR_NETWORK with the message "Http error: Internal Server Error"
Maybe we can change the BugzillaClient.connectInternal to throw an other Exeption
In other pass we should store some information from the Status on disk and add the timing information and maybe some code to disable the query when we have an error more then x times.
Thougths?

> Is there a performance difference between "contains" and "is" for the name > field?
More than likely. On the backend, "contains" will wrap the string with wildcards (WHERE field LIKE "%string%) whereas "is" is a direct comparison (WHERE field = "string").

> Statuscode == RepositoryStatus.ERROR_IO and the Exception is > SocketTimeoutException for Queries with LastSynchronizedTimeStamp = "<never>" > > when we change the socket timeout from 3 minutes to 4 minutes we get > RepositoryStatus.ERROR_NETWORK with the message "Http error: Internal Server > Error"
As far as I understand that's something specific to Eclipse.org. With other repositories we would get a socket timeout since query runs "forever", right?
> Maybe we can change the BugzillaClient.connectInternal to throw an other > exception
It would be optimal if we could recognize the timeouts by a particular error code. We could extend RepositoryStatus with a new code for that.
> In other pass we should store some information from the Status on disk and add > the timing information and maybe some code to disable the query when we have an > error more then x times.
That sounds very good. It makes sense to me to have a persistence mechanism for the state. I would not couple that to the IStatus though but use more extensible mechanism. As Denis suggested it could also make sense to store the execution time of the query to dynamically modify the interval for expensive queries.
It's somewhat related to bug 288689: [patch] exponentially increase repository configuration retrieval attempts if it is stale which suggest a similar mechanism for repository configuration refreshes.

(In reply to comment #13) > Should we then change the default for the operation from "contains" to "is"? > This may help in some cases but not for the query from attachment#227684
The Bugzilla web UI also uses contains. For fields such as comments or summary that do not only contain a single string using "is" isn't very helpful since users will rarely know the exact text. I'd prefer we keep "contains" as the default.
We could consider showing a warning though in the query dialog if a query looks expensive based on the provided search criteria.

(In reply to comment #15) > The Bugzilla web UI also uses contains. For fields such as comments or > summary that do not only contain a single string using "is" isn't very > helpful since users will rarely know the exact text. I'd prefer we keep > "contains" as the default.
The web UI never runs periodically, so ease of use/first time right trumps optimization. I'm OK with "contains" as default in regular text fields, but my hypothesis is that name fields have three main use cases:
- finding the bugs that you yourself reported, commented or are working on. This would cover 90% of cases is my estimate. - finding bugs to be triaged because they have been assigned to a generic userid, committers and contributors - finding the bugs for someone you are mentoring, so you can see his progress, even less people
I think Denis can do a slow query or log analysis and provide real numbers for how many people only search for their own bugs. (userID == searchedName)
If my hypothesis is correct, UI improvements will help the 90%: default name fields to "is" matching, AND making it super easy to enter your own user ID, using the "insert my User ID" trick from the "Add CC" field in the Task Editor. This is a change that will also optimize all queries that do not lead to time outs, saving Denis and the Foundation many cycles in the process.
Alternative is add query strength reduction to bugzilla: if search field == existing user id, reduce query from "contains" to "is"
> We could consider showing a warning though in the query dialog if a query > looks expensive based on the provided search criteria.
@Steffen: Can you please respond to the point that Mylyn should be well behaved and provide excessive length query feedback for ALL connectors? comment #10

Frank, I will take a look at these reviews when I get time, but it might be a while. Tomek, if you have a chance, it would be great if you could look at them and chime in with your thoughts on what we should do here.

(In reply to comment #15) > The Bugzilla web UI also uses contains.
And it's the default. Opening the query form with a different set of params pre-selected could be confusing. On the other hand, if this is changed on the server ("is" is the new default) we should respect that in the form.
Also, I'm a lazy guy and often enter just "zarna" when looking for my bugs. I don't care if it's my private address or the one I use at work. But this leads us to...
> We could consider showing a warning though in the query dialog if a query looks > expensive based on the provided search criteria.
I like that idea. Suggesting to narrow your search basing on a simple, heuristic algorithm would motive guys like me to improve their queries.
(In reply to comment #21) > I have updated my queries to use "is" instead of "contains." :)
We could make sure this happen automatically if content assist was used.
Another way of tackling this could be introduction of predefined query temples like "My bugs in component X", "Recently commented bugs in inbox" etc, similar to what you have in Gerrit. This would users to setup some of their queries with few clicks and allow us to optimize them at the same time.
However, all these improvements would only help us with new queries. Existing ones are still gonna time out, so displaying a warning that your queries are too complex _and_ suggesting how to fix them would be most helpful. Also, the algo could detect if one of your queries is contained in another one. Or that they overlap significantly. That could reduce the number of queries or encourage the user to make them more specific.
